 April 11, 1955) is the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|TX|8}}, serving since 1997. He is a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]]. The district includes a large swath of suburban and rural territory north of [[Houston, Texas|Houston]].\n\n==Early life, education, and early political career==\nBrady was born in [[Vermillion, South Dakota]], one of five children of William F. and Nancy A. Brady. His father, a lawyer, was killed in 1967 in a courtroom shooting in [[Rapid City, South Dakota|Rapid City]] when Brady was 12 years old.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=AP|title=Wild Shooting Spree Caught On Tape|journal=Daytona Beach Morning Journal|date=September 27, 1967|volume=XLII|issue=232|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=b24eAAAAIBAJ&sjid=mskEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3571%2C5262217|accessdate=December 17, 2015}}</ref> His mother was left to raise five children by herself. While at [[Central High School (Rapid City, South Dakota)|Central High School]], he was student body president and a four-sport athlete. He graduated in 1973. Working his way through college holding a variety of jobs\u2014construction worker, meat packer, manufacturing worker, waiter, and bartender, Brady earned a degree in mass communications from the [[University of South Dakota]] in Vermillion,<ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/elections/2004/candidates/22038/</ref> where he played varsity baseball, served in the student government association and became a member of the [[Lambda Chi Alpha]] fraternity. In 2005, he was named a distinguished alumnus of the university, and in 2001, was a recipient of the order of achievement by the national Lambda Chi Alpha organization.\n\nA chamber of commerce executive at the Rapid City area chamber of commerce, Brady was elected to the Rapid City common council, at age 26. In 1982, he moved to Texas to work for the Beaumont chamber of commerce and later the south Montgomery county, The Woodlands chamber of commerce.\n\n==Texas House of Representatives==\nBrady began his Texas political career in 1990 when he was elected to the [[Texas House of Representatives]], representing The Woodlands, parts of Montgomery County, and five other counties west and north of Houston.<ref>[http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=b000755 Brady, Kevin Patrick.] Biographical Directory of the United States Congress: 1774\u2013present. Retrieved on October 1, 2017.</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n===Tenure===\nIn 2002, Brady voted in favor of the [[Authorization for the Use of Military Force Against Iraq]], authorizing the [[2003 invasion of Iraq|U.S. invasion of Iraq]] the following year.<ref>[http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2002/roll455.xml Final Vote Results for Roll Call 455], On Passage, H.J.Res. 114 (107th): Authorization for Use of Military Force Against Iraq Resolution of 2002], Office of the Clerk of the House of Representatives.</ref>\n\nIn 2005, Brady was a chief supporter of the [[Dominican Republic-Central America Free Trade Agreement]] (DR-CAFTA), working with the [[George W. Bush administration]] to secure passage of that [[free-trade agreement]].<ref>Peter Baker, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2005/05/12/AR2005051201809.html Bush Brings In Backup to Help Sell CAFTA], ''Washington Post'' (May 13, 2005).</ref><ref>Howard Roden, [http://www.chron.com/neighborhood/article/Brady-to-spearhead-U-S-campaign-for-CAFTA-9789727.php Brady to spearhead U.S. campaign for CAFTA], ''Houston Chronicle'' (January 12, 2005).</ref><ref>[http://www.ncbfaa.org/Scripts/4Disapi.dll/4DCGI/cms/review.html?Action=CMS_Document&DocID=8993&MenuKey=news NCBFAA Honoring Rep. Brady For His Support on CAFTA] (press release), National Customs Brokers & Forwarders Association of America.</ref> In 2011, Brady also voted in favor of [[United States\u2013Korea Free Trade Agreement|free-trade agreements with South Korea]]<ref>[http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2011/roll783.xml Final Vote Results for Roll Call 783], On Passage, To implement the United States-Korea Trade Agreement, Office of the Clerk of the House of Representatives.</ref> [[United States\u2013Colombia Free Trade Agreement|Colombia]],<ref>[http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2011/roll781.xml Final Vote Results for Roll Call 781], On Passage, To implement the United States-Colombia Trade Promotion Agreement, Office of the Clerk of the House of Representatives.</ref> and [[Panama\u2013United States Trade Promotion Agreement|Panama]].<ref>[http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2011/roll782.xml Final Vote Results for Roll Call 782], On Passage, To implement the United States-Panama Trade Promotion Agreement.</ref> However, in 2017, Brady supports President [[Donald Trump]]'s proposed [[Border-adjustment tax (United States)|border adjustment tax]], arguing that the tax on imports would place the U.S. on a level playing field with other countries that have the tax and would raise an estimated $1 trillion for the federal budget.<ref name=\"ADaughtertyMcClat04192017\">{{cite news |last=Daugherty |first=Alex |date=April 19, 2017 |title=Congress\u2019 top tax man isn\u2019t waiting for Trump\u2019s blessing to get going on an overhaul |url=http://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/politics-government/congress/article145569729.html |work=[[The McClatchy Company]] |location=[[Sacramento, California]] |access-date=April 24, 2017 |quote=He won re-election last fall with 53 percent of the vote after being challenged by three conservative Republicans in a primary, and his public role in a national tax debate could spur another challenge in 2018.}}</ref>\n\nBrady is known as the author of a federal \"[[sunset clause|sunset law]]\" that would require every federal program not specifically written into the [[U.S. Constitution|Constitution]] to justify its existence to taxpayers within 12 years or face elimination.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.texastribune.org/directory/kevin-brady/ |title=U.S. Rep. Kevin Brady |publisher=The Texas Tribune |date=November 4, 1955 |accessdate=August 29, 2010}}</ref>\n\nBrady is the chairman of the U.S. House\u2013Senate joint economic committee, the third Texan to lead the committee, after Sen. [[Lloyd Bentsen]] and Rep. [[Wright Patman]].{{Citation needed|date=September 2017}}\n\nIn March 2012, he proposed the Sound Dollar Act, legislation to require the [[Federal Reserve System|Federal Reserve]] to [[Gold standard|monitor gold]] and the [[Foreign exchange market|foreign-exchange value]] of the U.S. dollar. The bill would also repeal the Federal Reserve's dual mandate (controlling unemployment and inflation) and replace it with a single mandate for U.S. dollar [[price stability]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/articles/293730/king-dollar-will-cut-oil-prices-larry-kudlow|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812060553/http://www.nationalreview.com/articles/293730/king-dollar-will-cut-oil-prices-larry-kudlow|title=King Dollar Will Cut Oil Prices|author=Larry Kudlow|archivedate=August 12, 2014|work=National Review Online}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2015, Brady was elected the 65th chairman of the [[United States House Committee on Ways and Means|Committee on Ways and Means]].<ref name=\"WalshCNN11042015\">{{cite news|last=Walsh|first=Deirdre|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/11/04/politics/kevin-brady-ways-and-means|title=Texas Republican Kevin Brady to be new Ways and Means chairman|publisher=CNN|date=2015-11-04|accessdate=2016-01-21}}</ref> As of 2017, Brady serves as chairman of the [[United States House Committee on Ways and Means|Committee on Ways and Means]].\n\nIn March 2017, Brady introduced an amendment to the [[American Health Care Act]] (the House Republican proposal to repeal the [[Affordable Care Act]]) that would allow health insurance providers to fully deduct all forms of compensation to their most highly compensated executives without limit, repealing the current law, which capped the deduction at $500,000 per executive. ''Los Angeles Times'' columnist [[Michael Hiltzik]] criticized Brady's amendment as a \"secret payoff\" to the health insurance industry because of the cryptic language of Brady's amendment.<ref>[https://waysandmeans.house.gov/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/20170308-Amendment-in-the-Nature-of-a-Substitute-to-Subtitle-__-Budget-Reconciliation-Legislative-Recommendations-Relating-to-Remuneration-from-Certain-Insurers.pdf Amendment in the Nature of a Substitute to the Committee Print Relating to Remuneration from Certain Insurers Offered by Mr. Brady of Texas]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/business/hiltzik/la-fi-hiltzik-obamacare-ceos-20170307-story.html |title=Here's the secret payoff to health insurance CEOs buried in the GOP Obamacare repeal bill |publisher=Los Angeles Times |date=March 6, 2017 |accessdate=June 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAs chairman of the House Committee on Ways and Means, Brady opposed a resolution to request ten years' worth of returns from President Trump and his business entities.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.northjersey.com/story/news/new-jersey/2017/09/07/trumps-taxes-stay-secret-committee-rejects-maneuver-pascrell/642085001/|title=Trump's taxes stay secret as committee rejects maneuver by Pascrell|work=North Jersey|access-date=2017-09-09|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nj.com/politics/index.ssf/2017/09/pascrell_tries_again_to_get_trumps_tax_returns.html|title=Here's what happened when Pascrell made another pitch to get Trump's tax returns|work=NJ.com|access-date=2017-09-09|language=en-US}}</ref> Brady said that the resolution was an abuse done for \"obvious political purposes\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/policy/finance/349699-house-panel-rejects-measure-to-seek-trumps-tax-returns|title=House panel rejects measure to seek Trump's tax returns|last=Jagoda|first=Naomi|date=2017-09-07|work=TheHill|access-date=2017-09-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2017/09/05/trump-tax-returns-242358|title=House panel to take up Trump tax return resolution|work=POLITICO|access-date=2017-09-09}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, House Speaker [[Paul Ryan]] designated Brady as the leader of his Tax Reform Task Force.<ref>[https://abetterway.speaker.gov/_assets/pdf/ABetterWay-Tax-PolicyPaper.pdf A Better Way], Speaker Paul Ryan, June 24, 2016.</ref>\n\nIn November 2017, Brady said that the [[Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017]] would provide \"tax relief at every level\"; in fact, 7 percent of households in 2018 would pay ''more'' in taxes and by 2022, one quarter of households would pay ''more''.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.factcheck.org/2017/11/cherry-picking-tax-cut-estimates/|title=Cherry-Picking Tax Cut Estimates - FactCheck.org|date=2017-11-29|work=FactCheck.org|access-date=2017-12-02|language=en-US}}</ref> Brady's claim that 70% of the tax cuts in the bill would go to households making below $200,000 was found to be \"misleading\" by [[FactCheck.org|FactCheck.Org]] and \"cherry-picked\" by [[PolitiFact]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2017/nov/30/kevin-brady/does-70-percent-tax-bills-relief-go-those-making-u/|title=Does 70% of tax bill benefits go to families under $200,000?|work=@politifact|access-date=2017-12-02|language=en}}</ref> FactCheck.org noted that \"57.7 percent of the tax relief goes to those families making less than $200,000 in 2019 \u2014 not the 70 percent that Brady cited for 2019. By 2027, 50 percent of tax relief as a result of business and individual income tax changes would go to those making more than $200,000 a year.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Elections===\n\n;1996\nIncumbent Republican congressman [[Jack Fields]] of [[Texas' 8th congressional district]] decided to retire. Brady decided to run and ranked second in the Republican primary with 22% of the vote in a six candidate field. But the candidate who ranked first, Dr. Gene Fontenot, received just 36% of the vote, short of the 50% threshold.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=222672|title=Our Campaigns \u2013 TX District 8 \u2013 R Primary Race \u2013 Mar 12, 1996|publisher=}}</ref> In the run-off election, Brady defeated him 53%\u201347%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=222682|title=Our Campaigns \u2013 TX District 8 \u2013 R Runoff Race \u2013 Apr 09, 1996|publisher=}}</ref> However, the [[Supreme Court of the United States]] ruled in ''[[Bush v. Vera]]'' that three congressional districts in Texas were unconstitutional.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.austinchronicle.com/news/2012-03-09/texas-redistricting-a-timeline/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303224441/http://www.austinchronicle.com/news/2012-03-09/texas-redistricting-a-timeline/|title=Texas Redistricting: A Timeline|archivedate=March 3, 2016|publisher=}}</ref> After holding hearings, the court concluded that there was no longer time to hold primaries and instead forced all candidates (Democrats and Republicans) be listed together on the November general election ballot in a [[jungle primary]]. If no candidate reached 50%, a special runoff would be held on December 10 between the two highest ranking candidates regardless of political party. In the November election, Brady ranked first with 41% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=30056|title=Our Campaigns \u2013 TX District 8 Race \u2013 Nov 05, 1996|publisher=}}</ref> In the December run-off election, he defeated Fontenot again 59%\u201341%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=30083|title=Our Campaigns \u2013 TX District 8 \u2013 Runoff Race \u2013 Dec 10, 1996|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n;1998\u20132008\nDuring this time period, he never won re-election with less than 67% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/CandidateDetail.html?CandidateID=1744|title=Our Campaigns \u2013 Candidate \u2013 Kevin P. Brady|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n;2010\u20132012\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Texas, 2010#District 8}}\nFor the first time since 1998, Brady was challenged in the Republican primary. Three candidates filed against him. He defeated all of them in the March primary with 79% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=612091|title=Our Campaigns \u2013 TX District 08 \u2013 R Primary Race \u2013 Mar 02, 2010|publisher=}}</ref> He won re-election with 80% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=524824|title=Our Campaigns \u2013 TX \u2013 District 08 Race \u2013 Nov 02, 2010|publisher=}}</ref> In the May 2012, Republican primary in a newly-redrawn district he defeated his challenger with 76% of the vote. In the November 6, 2012 general election he defeated his Democratic opponent with over 77% of the vote.\n\n;2014\n\nIn the Republican primary on March 4, Brady won re-nomination to a tenth term in the U.S. House. He polled 41,549 votes (68 percent) to 19,508 (32 percent) for his intraparty challenger, Craig McMichael.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://team1.sos.state.tx.us/enr/results/mar04_169_state.htm?x=0&y=218&id=176 |title=Republican primary election returns, March 4, 2014 |publisher=enr.sos.state.tx.us |accessdate=March 5, 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140305180619/https://team1.sos.state.tx.us/enr/results/mar04_169_state.htm?x=0&y=218&id=176 |archivedate=March 5, 2014 |df= }}</ref>\n\nIn the General election held November 4, 2014 Brady was re-elected to his seat in the U.S. House. He polled 124,897 votes (89.32 percent) to 14,930 (10.67 percent) for his challenger, Ken Petty.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://team1.sos.state.tx.us/enr/results/nov04_175_state.htm?x=0&y=2480&id=565|title=2014 General election returns|publisher=enr.sos.state.tx.us|accessdate=November 6, 2014}}</ref>\n\n;2016\n\nIn November 2015, [[Steve Toth]], a former State Representative from [[The Woodlands, Texas]], announced that he would be running against Brady, facing what could be Brady's toughest campaign.<ref>{{cite news |last=Tresaugue |first=Matthew |date=November 17, 2015 |title=Former state lawmaker Toth to challenge US Rep. Brady |url=http://www.chron.com/neighborhood/woodlands/news/article/Former-state-lawmaker-to-challenge-Brady-6638392.php |newspaper=[[Houston Chronicle]] |location=[[Houston, Texas]] |access-date=January 7, 2016 |quote=A former state lawmaker from The Woodlands will mount a Republican primary challenge to U.S. Rep. Kevin Brady, the House's newest and perhaps most powerful committee chairman.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Tresaugue |first=Matthew |date=December 20, 2015 |title=As Rep. Brady rises on Capitol Hill, he faces primary challenge at home |url=http://www.houstonchronicle.com/neighborhood/woodlands/news/article/As-Rep-Brady-rises-on-Capitol-Hill-he-faces-6711766.php |newspaper=[[Houston Chronicle]] |location=[[Houston, Texas]] |access-date=January 7, 2016 |quote=In this highly charged election season, the race between Brady and Steve Toth reflects tensions within the Republican Party's conservative wing.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Mekelburg |first=Madlin |date=December 14, 2015 |title=Surprise Congressional Challenge Marks Close of Filing |url=http://www.texastribune.org/2015/12/14/filing-deadline-today/ |newspaper=[[Texas Tribune]] |location=[[Austin, Texas]] |access-date=January 7, 2016 |quote=U.S. Rep. Kevin Brady, R-The Woodlands, faces three primary challengers, including former state Rep. Steve Toth.}}</ref>\n\nKevin Brady eked out a victory in the March 1, 2016 primary, but he is likely to have a target on his back for years to come.<ref name=TXTribIncumbentsSafe>{{cite web|url=http://www.texastribune.org/2016/03/01/texas-congressional-races-incumbents-safe-so-far/|title=In Texas Congressional Races, Incumbents Stay Safe|work=The Texas Tribune}}</ref>  Toth held Brady to 53% of the vote, the lowest re-election total in his 18-year career.<ref name=TXTribIncumbentsSafe/><ref name=\"MSmithTXTrib03012016\">{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Morgan |last2=Livingston |first2=Abby |date=March 1, 2016 |title=In Texas Congressional Races, Incumbents Stay Safe |url=http://www.texastribune.org/2016/03/01/texas-congressional-races-incumbents-safe-so-far/ |newspaper=[[Texas Tribune]] |location=[[Austin, Texas]] |access-date=March 2, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"TXSecState03022016\">{{cite news |date=March 2, 2016 |title=U.S. Representative District 8 |url=https://enrpages.sos.state.tx.us/public/mar01_273_race6.htm?x=0&y=155&id=802 |newspaper=[[Secretary of State of Texas|Texas Secretary of State]] |location=[[Austin, Texas]] |access-date=March 2, 2016}}</ref>  In 2014, Brady received 68% of the vote in the primary.<ref name=\"MSmithTXTrib03012016\"/>  Brady spent over $1.5 million.<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=February 10, 2016 |title=Rep. Kevin Brady |url=https://www.opensecrets.org/politicians/summary.php?cid=N00005883|publisher=[[Center for Responsive Politics]] |newspaper=[[OpenSecrets.org]] |location=[[Washington, DC]] |access-date=March 2, 2016}}</ref>  Toth spent $89,325.<ref name=\"RElliottHousChron03022016\">{{cite news |last1=Elliott |first1=Rebecca |last2=Tresaugue |first2=Matthew |date=March 2, 2016 |title=Green holds off Garcia; Brady, Culberson stave off challenges |url=http://www.houstonchronicle.com/news/politics/houston/article/Green-holds-off-Garcia-Brady-Culberson-stave-6864840.php |newspaper=[[Houston Chronicle]] |location=[[Houston, Texas]] |access-date=March 2, 2016|quote=His challengers said Brady has compromised too often, most recently by voting for a year-end spending measure that conservative activists say lacked limits on Planned Parenthood or on refugees from Syria and Iraq.}}</ref>  Toth criticized Brady for compromising too often with President Obama<ref name=\"RElliottHousChron03022016\"/> and was critical of Brady for supporting the omnibus federal budget bill and voting to revive the [[Export-Import Bank of the United States|U.S. Export-Import Bank]].<ref name=\"MRecioMcClat02292016\">{{cite news |last=Recio |first=Maria |date=February 29, 2016 |title=Texas primary down-ballot drama: Congress members on the brink |url=http://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/politics-government/election/article63208022.html#storylink=cpy |newspaper=[[The McClatchy Company|McClatchyDC]] |location=[[Washington, DC]] |access-date=March 2, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Ways and Means|Committee on Ways and Means]]''' ( current Chairman)\n\nDuring his time in congress he has served as a chair on the [[Joint Economic Committee]], [[Ways and Means Committee]], and the [[United States Congress Joint Committee on Taxation|Joint Committee on taxation]].\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n* Army Caucus\n* Congressional Missing and Exploited Children Caucus\n* Congressional Rural Caucus\n*[[United States Congressional International Conservation Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Our Members|author=|url=https://royce.house.gov/internationalconservation/members.html|format=|publisher=U.S. House of Representatives International Conservation Caucus |date=|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref>\n* Sportsmen's Caucus\n*[[Congressional Constitution Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://congressionalconstitutioncaucus-garrett.house.gov/about-us/membership|format=|publisher=Congressional Constitution Caucus|date=|accessdate=8 May 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Congressional Western Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://westerncaucus.house.gov/about/membership.htm|format=|publisher=Congressional Western Caucus|date=|accessdate=27 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBrady lives in [[The Woodlands, Texas|The Woodlands]], a [[suburb]] of Houston, with his wife Cathy and two young sons (Will and Sean).<ref>{{cite web|title=About Kevin Brady|url=http://kevinbrady.house.gov/about|accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2005, Brady was arrested and charged with [[driving under the influence]] of alcohol while in South Dakota.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/nation/2005-10-11-drunk-congressman_x.htm|title=Texas Congressman Kevin Brady charged with DUI|agency=Associated Press|date=October 11, 2005}}</ref> He pleaded no contest, was convicted of a misdemeanor, and fined $350. Brady issued an apology.<ref>Samantha Levine, [http://www.chron.com/neighborhood/woodlands-news/article/U-S-Rep-Brady-pleads-no-contest-to-DUI-charge-1517728.php U.S. Rep. Brady pleads no contest to DUI charge], ''Houston Chronicle'' (November 9, 2005).</ref>\n\nHe has received many awards including:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/361/kevin-brady#.W6TzbRJKjBI|title=The Voter's Self Defense System|website=Vote Smart|language=en-US|access-date=2018-09-21}}</ref>\n\n* Five Outstanding Young Texas Honoree, 1994\n* Hometown Hero, The Woodlands, Texas\n* Spirit of Enterprise Award\n* Guardian of Small Business Award\n* Savior of Gnomes Award\n* Golden Bulldog Award, Watchdogs of The Treasury\n* Special Recognition, Citizens Against Government Waste\n\nIn his free time he enjoys playing on the GOP baseball team and eating beaver nuggets from Buc-ee's<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/RepKevinBrady/status/1034487652685410306|title=Rep. Kevin Brady on Twitter|website=Twitter|language=en|access-date=2018-09-21}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://kevinbrady.house.gov Congressman Kevin Brady] official U.S. House website\n* [http://www.bradyforcongress.com Kevin Brady for Congress]\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Texas/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Kevin_Brady_%5BR-8%5D}}\n* {{CongLinks | congbio=b000755 | votesmart=361 | fec=H6TX08100 | congress=kevin-brady/B000755 }}\n* {{C-SPAN|kevinbrady}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n